Both additions are correct and in the right place. Here's a summary of every change made — all purely additive, touching no existing handlers or the header:

---

### What was added to `common/chat.cpp`

**1. New handler function** (inserted just before the `workaround` namespace, ~line 1519):

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // The Jinja template itself handles the [INST]/[/INST] wrapping, system-message
    // prepending, and </s> suffixing on assistant turns, so apply it directly.
    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    // Preserve the structural markers so the tokenizer keeps them as single tokens.
    data.preserved_tokens  = { "[INST]", "[/INST]" };

    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 has no native tool-call syntax in the template,
    // so the output parser is content-only.
    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest()) + p.end();
    });
    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**2. Auto-detection block** (appended at the bottom of `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, just before `return std::nullopt`):

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - wraps user turns with [INST]/[/INST], prepends system
// messages to the first user turn, and appends </s> after assistant turns.
// Distinguish from Ministral/Mistral Large 3, which uses [SYSTEM_PROMPT] instead.
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

---

**Design decisions:**

- **Detection** — requires `[INST]` and `[/INST]` to be present in the template source, and `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` to be absent. The Ministral 3 handler is checked first in the dispatcher and requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so there is no overlap; the absence check is an explicit belt-and-suspenders guard per the spec.
- **Prompt rendering** — delegated entirely to `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`, which runs the model's own Jinja template. That template already encodes the exact v0.3 rules (system prepended to the first `[INST]` block, `</s>` after each assistant turn), so no manual message-stitching is needed in the handler.
- **Parser** — content-only (`p.prefix` → `p.content(p.rest())` → `p.end()`), matching the format's lack of a native structured tool-call syntax.
- **No header changes** — `COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE` is already defined and used by other simple handlers (GigaChatV3, etc.), so no new enum values are required.

